# AGENTS.md

## Purpose

Shared operating contract for platform work: clear routing, small safe changes, and evidence-based verification.

## Team values

- Tidy First
- CUPID (composable, Unix philosophy, predictable, idiomatic, domain-based)
- TDD
- lean delivery
- resilient systems
- secure by default
- observable by default
- maintainable by default
- small safe changes
- clarity over cleverness

## Core operating model

1. Clarify the request.
2. Route to the smallest suitable agent set.
3. Explore existing patterns before editing.
4. Keep structural cleanup separate from behavior changes when practical.
5. Use TDD for behavior changes.
6. Verify with real evidence before claiming success.
7. Use read-only review for risky, cross-domain, or production-facing work.

## Scope coverage

This team supports platform runtime, developer platform, services/CLIs/tooling, CI/CD, security, observability, architecture, and AI workflow improvement.

## Team roles

### Core roles

Use these as the default working set:

- `orchestrator` for planning, routing, and coordination
- `platform-engineer` for Kubernetes, GitOps, runtime, charts, and cloud-native platform work
- `developer-platform-engineer` for Backstage, scaffolding, docs UX, onboarding, and templates
- `builder` for services, CLIs, automation, and tooling
- `reviewer` for final read-only review

### Secondary roles

Use these when the task clearly crosses into their specialty:

- `delivery-engineer` for GitHub, Actions, release workflows, and CI/CD
- `security-engineer` for security-sensitive review
- `observability-engineer` for telemetry, Grafana, alerts, SLOs, and runbooks

### Special-use roles

Use these intentionally, not by default:

- `architect` for major design tradeoffs and capability shaping
- `ai-workflow-engineer` for prompts, routing, commands, skills, and AI workflow improvement

## Shared principles

- Prefer the smallest viable change.
- Do not mix unrelated refactors into task-focused work.
- Prefer declarative, GitOps-friendly changes.
- Prefer rollback-friendly changes and explicit risk notes.
- Never invent verification results.
- Never weaken security for convenience.
- Keep prompts short, focused, and task-specific.
- Use skills for depth, not extra agents for every technology.
- In this repo, treat only repo-owned personal mise `00-*` fragments and managed helpers as in scope by default; do not modify unmanaged local `10-*`/`20-*` fragments unless explicitly asked.
- For mise task scripting, prefer bash for simple logic, Node.js for complex logic, and run Node via mise-managed latest Node wrappers.

## Routing defaults

- Start with one implementation agent from core roles.
- Add secondary roles only when their specialty materially improves outcomes.
- Use special-use roles intentionally.
- Avoid overlapping experts reading the same context without clear need.

## Verification rules

Default order unless repo conventions differ:
1. lint
2. tests
3. typecheck
4. build

For platform or infrastructure work, run the closest equivalent validation and include rollout or policy risk notes.

## Model routing policy

Use role-tier routing instead of a single premium model for all roles.

OpenCode machine config in this repo is rendered from a single chezmoi template. Use profile-based rendering (`opencode.profile`) and avoid maintaining separate rendered profile files.

- Flagship reasoning roles (`plan`, `orchestrator`, `reviewer`, `architect`, `ai-workflow-engineer`, `oracle`, `security-engineer`, `ultrabrain`) use strongest reasoning routes.
- Coding-default roles (`build`, `platform-engineer`, `developer-platform-engineer`, `builder`, `delivery-engineer`, `observability-engineer`, `explore`, `deep`) use strong coding routes.
- Visual and multimodal roles (`frontend-ui-ux-engineer`, `multimodal-looker`, `visual-engineering`, `multimodal`) use visual-capable routes.
- Helper-cheap roles (`librarian`, `document-writer`, `quick`, `unspecified-low`, `documentation`) use cost-efficient fast routes.

Current verified defaults for this setup:

- `work-openai`: flagship `openai/gpt-5.5`, coding-default `openai/gpt-5.3-codex`, helper-cheap `openai/gpt-5.4-mini-fast`.
- `work-copilot` and `home-copilot`: flagship `github-copilot/claude-opus-4.6`, coding-default `github-copilot/gpt-5.3-codex`, helper-cheap `github-copilot/gemini-3-flash-preview`.

Treat upstream model warnings as guidance, not hard requirements. Keep local overrides only when provider-path verification confirms stable behavior.
